main event: A round, white object the size of a first magnitude star was observed moving steadily upward until it disappeared behind a low cloud.
interesting points: The object was observed for 13 minutes, moving from a bearing of 030 degrees true at an altitude of 38 degrees to a bearing of 045 degrees true at an altitude of 15 degrees.
The report mentions that a check with the timetable for the Echo I satellite indicates it was moving toward the path of this sighting, which is likely the cause.
The observers were Coast Guard personnel, COD and CO, from Corpus Christi, Texas.
The weather conditions at the time included thunderstorms in the area, with varying cloud cover and wind speeds at different altitudes.
No other unusual activity or conditions were reported, and no other reports of unidentified objects were received from the area.
sighted object: round, white object the size of a first magnitude star
location: 8 miles east of Corpus Christi, Texas
witnesses: Coast Guard personnel COD and CO
